{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2012}}
The '''2006 North American ''E. coli'' outbreak''' was an [[Escherichia coli O157:H7]] outbreak from [[spinach]].<ref>Subcommittee of the PHLS Advisory Committee on Gastrointestinal Infections (2000). Guidelines for the control of infection with Vero cytotoxin producing Escherichia coli (VTEC). Communicable Dis Public Health; 3: 14–23. Available online at http://www.hpa.org.uk/cdph/issues/CDPHvol3/No1/vtec.pdf {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6kvLmZu|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> The  outbreak occurred in September 2006 and its probable origin was an Angus cattle ranch that had leased land to spinach grower.<ref name="Raine">{{cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2007/03/23/BAGJDOQM1H8.DTL|title=San Benito County ranch source of tainted spinach|date=March 23, 2007|work=San Francisco Chronicle | first=George | last=Raine|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6ngAyBT |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref> At least 276 consumer illnesses and 3 deaths have been attributed to the tainted produce.<ref name="cdc">{{cite web |url = http://www.cdc.gov/foodborne/ecolispinach/current.htm | title = Update on Multi-State Outbreak of E. coli O157:H7 Infections From Fresh Spinach | date = October 3, 2006 | work = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |accessdate =October 6, 2006|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6kx9kFd |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=[[Libby Sander]] |title=Source of Deadly E. Coli Is Found |url=http://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/13/us/13spinach.html?scp=6&sq=E.%20coli%20spinach&st=cse |quote=Cattle manure collected from a California ranch under investigation by federal and state authorities contains the same strain of E. coli that killed three people and sickened nearly 200 in a recent outbreak linked to tainted spinach, federal and state food safety officials said Thursday. ... |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date= October 13, 2006 |accessdate=October 10, 2011 }}</ref>

== History ==
In September 2006, there was an outbreak of [[food-borne illness]] caused by ''[[Escherichia coli]]'' (''E. coli'') bacteria found in uncooked [[spinach]]<ref name="fda14">{{cite web|url=http://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2006/ucm108731.htm|title=FDA Warning on Serious Foodborne E.coli O157:H7 Outbreak|date=September 14, 2006|accessdate=November 23, 2009|work=[[Food and Drug Administration (United States)]]|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6kxay5k |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref> in 26 U.S. states.<ref name="cdc" />

By October 6, 2006 199 people had been infected, including three people who died and 31 who suffered a type of kidney failure called [[hemolytic uremic syndrome]]<ref name="cdc" />
after eating spinach contaminated with the [[Escherichia coli O157:H7|''E. coli'' O157:H7]], a potentially deadly bacterium that causes bloody [[diarrhea]] and dehydration.<ref name="reuters">{{cite news|url=http://today.reuters.co.uk/news/articlenews.aspx?type=scienceNews&storyID=2006-09-17T022232Z_01_N14336072_RTRIDST_0_SCIENCE-ECOLI-DC.XML&pageNumber=1&imageid=∩=&sz=13&WTModLoc=NewsArt-C1-ArticlePage1|title=U.S. expands warning to cover all fresh spinach|date=September 17, 2006|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> This strain is more potent than in any other food poisoning scares. Federal health officials said half of those reported sick have been hospitalized, compared to 25 to 30 percent in past outbreaks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wfsb.com/health/9894017/detail.html|title=E. coli On Spinach May Have Been Extra Potent|date=September 20, 2006|work=[[WFSB]]|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nfLyjU |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>

The [[Food and Drug Administration (United States)|U.S. Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA) called for bagged fresh spinach to be removed from shelves and warned people not to eat any kind of fresh spinach or fresh spinach-containing products.<ref name="reuters"/><ref name="fda17"/> The FDA has also speculated that washing the spinach is insufficient to sanitize it because the bacteria is systemic, meaning that it is not just on the outside of the spinach, but that it has been absorbed through the [[root]]s and is now inside the spinach.  This hypothesis has since been deemed only hypothetical as there is no evidence that this can happen in spinach. The FDA has since reduced its warning to certain brands with specific dates.

The [[Canadian Food Inspection Agency]] has advised consumers not to eat fresh spinach from the U.S., including bagged, loose in bulk or in salad blends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inspection.gc.ca/english/corpaffr/recarapp/2006/20060918e.shtml|title=Expanded health hazad alert. Various brands of imported fresh spinach may contain E. coli 0157:H7 bacteria|date=September 18, 2006|work=[[Canadian Food Inspection Agency|CFIA]]|accessdate=September 26, 2006 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060925031217/http://www.inspection.gc.ca/english/corpaffr/recarapp/2006/20060918e.shtml  |archivedate = September 25, 2006}}</ref>

== Cause==
[[File:Angus cattle 5.jpg|thumb|right|'''Angus Cattle'''<br>The probable origin of the first outbreak was an Angus cattle ranch that had leased land to a spinach grower.]]
<!-- 6/5/2011 - replaced copyrighted image with PD image from USGOV-USDA -->

The outbreak was traced to organic [[Plastic shopping bag|bagged]] fresh [[spinach]]—sold as conventional produce—grown on a {{convert|50|acre|m2|sing=on}} farm in San Benito County, California. Investigators with the [[Centers for Disease Control]] initially speculated that the dangerous strain of bacteria, [[E. coli O157:H7]], originated from irrigation water contaminated with cattle feces or from grazing [[deer]].<ref>
{{cite news |url=http://www.salon.com/news/feature/2006/09/22/e_coli/|title=The truth about the E. coli outbreak|date=September 22, 2006|publisher=[[Salon.com]]| accessdate= 25 September 2006 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

A follow-up report by the CDC<ref name="autogenerated3">
{{cite news |url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2007/March/24/local/stories/12local.htm|title=Inside the CDC's report on the deadly E. coli spinach outbreak|date=March 24, 2007|publisher=[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]| accessdate= 6 April 2007 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> and a joint report by the California Department of Health Services (CDHS) and U.S. FDA<ref name="Raine"/><ref>
{{cite news |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/17755937/|title=Source of tainted spinach finally pinpointed|date=March 23, 2007|publisher=MSNBC| accessdate= 6 April 2007 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> concluded that the probable source of the outbreak was Paicines Ranch, an Angus cattle ranch that had leased land to spinach grower Mission Organics. The report found 26 samples of ''E. coli'' “indistinguishable from the outbreak strain” in water and cattle manure on the San Benito County ranch, some within a mile from the tainted spinach fields. Although officials could not definitively say how the spinach became contaminated, both reports named the presence of wild pigs on the ranch and the proximity of surface waterways to irrigation wells as "potential environmental risk factors."<ref name=autogenerated3 /> The reports also noted that flaws in the spinach producer's transportation and processing systems could have further spread contamination. Paicines Ranch is not under investigation for its alleged role in the outbreak.

Soon after the reports were released, California's farm industry announced that it will adopt a set of "good agricultural practices" to reduce the risk of ''E. coli'' contamination for leafy green vegetables.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2007/March/24/local/stories/13local.htm|title=Tainted spinach linked to Paicines Ranch: Officials say San Juan Bautista plant though failed to follow its own safety procedures|date=March 24, 2007|publisher=[[Santa Cruz Sentinel]]|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070930201158/http%3A//www.santacruzsentinel.com/archive/2007/March/24/local/stories/13local.htm |archivedate = September 30, 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Those participating in the voluntary program will be eligible for product seal of approval.

Two companies in California voluntarily recalled spinach and spinach-containing products: [[Natural Selection Foods LLC]],<ref name="nsfoods">[http://www.nsfoods.com/ Natural Selection Foods] {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6ngwtKF|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> based in [[San Juan Bautista, California|San Juan Bautista]], and [[River Ranch Fresh Foods]].<ref name="fda17">{{cite web |url=http://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2006/ucm109578.htm|title=FDA Statement on Foodborne E. coli O157:H7 Outbreak in Spinach|date=September 17, 2006| work= Food and Drug Administration (United States)|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nh6l4r |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref><ref name="nsfoods"/><ref name="linked">{{cite news|title=FDA: E. coli linked to Natural Selection Foods|date=September 15, 2006|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/HEALTH/09/15/tainted.spinach.ap/index.html|publisher=CNN|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060921110045/http%3A//www.cnn.com/2006/HEALTH/09/15/tainted.spinach.ap/index.html |archivedate = September 21, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Natural Selection brands include Natural Selection Foods, Pride of San Juan, [[Earthbound Farm]], Bellissima, [[Dole Food Company|Dole]], Rave Spinach, Emeril, Sysco, O Organic, Fresh Point, River Ranch, Superior, Nature's Basket, Pro-Mark, Compliments, [[Trader Joe's]], Jansal Valley, Cheney Brothers, D'Arrigo Brothers, Green Harvest, Mann, Mills Family Farm, Premium Fresh, Snoboy, The Farmer's Market, Tanimura & Antle, President's Choice, Cross Valley, and Riverside Farms. Affected brands from River Ranch include [[Hy-Vee]], Farmer's Market and Fresh and Easy. Later, a third company, RLB Food Distributors, issued a multiple [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast states]] recall of spinach-containing salad products for possible ''E. coli'' contamination.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fda.gov/Safety/Recalls/ArchiveRecalls/2006/ucm112044.htm| title=RLB Food Distributors Issues a Multiple East Coast States Recall of Fresh Spinach Salad Products for Possible E. coli Contamination|date=September 20, 2006|work=Food and Drug Administration (United States)|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nhTnS8 |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref> Natural Selection Foods announced on September 18, 2006 that its organic produce had been cleared of contamination by an independent agency, but did not lift the recalls on any of its organic brands.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2006-09-17-spinach_x.htm| title=Company says organic spinach OK, but E. coli recall still in effect|date=September 18, 2006|work=USA Today|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nhbHmg |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref> On September 22, Earthbound Farm announced that the FDA and the CDHS confirmed that its organic spinach had not been contaminated with ''E. coli''.

