=== Economic impact ===
In California, where three-quarters of all domestically grown spinach is harvested, farmers could face up to $74 million in losses due to the ''E. coli'' outbreak. In 2005, the spinach crop in California was valued at $258.3 million, and each acre lost amounts to a roughly $3,500 loss for the farmer.<ref>[http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/15095551/ October 2, 2006 and in October 4, 2006 AP story reported on MSNBC.com] {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6niujXD|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

=== Online Help ===
The [[Pulsenet|PulseNet system]], part of the Association of Public Health Laboratories and coordinated by CDC, detected clusters of infection in two states, Oregon and Wisconsin, which initiated investigations in each state. The first cluster was detected on Friday September 8 in one state, and the second cluster emerged in the second state on Wednesday September 13, by which time PulseNet had also identified potential associated cases in other states.<ref name="autogenerated1">[http://www.cdc.gov/ecoli/2006/september/response/091606.htm CDC | E. coli Outbreak From Spinach | What CDC and Other Agencies Are Doing – Sep. 16, 2006] {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6njHImh|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

The OutbreakNet, a group of state public health officers who investigate foodborne infection outbreaks, shared information with CDC that indicated that Oregon and Wisconsin were considering the same hypothesis: fresh spinach was the possible vehicle of infection. The group tracked and updated the increasing case count and exposure information. During a multistate call on Thursday, September 14, the group noted that the data strongly suggested that fresh spinach was a likely source. Within 24 hours of the outbreak, the data indicated that the outbreak was probably ongoing.<ref name=autogenerated1 />

CDC made communication to the public a priority by developing press releases, coordinating with FDA on press documents, conducting interviews with major media, and sending out notices on Thursday September 14 to the public health community via the Health Alert Network (HAN) and the Epidemic Information Exchange (Epi-X). By the next morning, the news media warned the U.S. population not to eat bagged spinach, with remarkable coverage.<ref name=autogenerated1 />

== Timeline ==
=== September ===
On September 14, 2006, the FDA warned consumers about an ''E. coli'' outbreak that was tied to bags of fresh spinach. The FDA reported that they received complaints from 19 states in the United States.<ref name="fda14"/><ref name="linked"/> The FDA advised "that consumers not eat bagged fresh spinach."<ref name="fda14"/> Three days later, their updated warning said not to eat "fresh spinach or fresh spinach-containing products."<ref name="fda17"/>
On September 17, the United States expanded the warning to avoid all fresh spinach.<ref name="reuters"/> The [[Centers for Disease Control]] issued an official ''Health Alert'', the highest category of alert message, on September 14<ref>[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]: [http://www2a.cdc.gov/HAN/ArchiveSys/ViewMsgV.asp?AlertNum=00249 Multiple States Investigating a Large Outbreak of E. coli O157:H7 Infections], September 14, 2006 {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6njRGGV|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> and started to investigate the ''E. coli'' outbreak. Wisconsin Governor [[Jim Doyle]] formally requested [[federal aid]] on September 15. His office said the CDC will help assess the causes and the magnitude of the outbreak in his state.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.channel3000.com/health/9865564/detail.html|date=September 16, 2006|title=CDC Starts To Investigate E. coli Outbreak In Wisconsin|publisher=[[WISC-TV]]|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6njiGFb |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>

On September 17, just three days after the initial warning, the FDA issued an updated warning stating that the public should "not eat fresh spinach or fresh spinach containing products."<ref name="fda17"/>

On September 18, [[Illinois]] and [[Nebraska]] reported their first cases of ''E. coli'' infection due to spinach, bringing the total number of affected states to 21. Ohio public health officials are investigating a 2-year-old's death that may also be linked.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.daytondailynews.com/n/content/oh/story/news/state/2006/09/18/ddn091806ohecoli.html|date=September 18, 2006|title=Ohio tot's death may be linked to tainted spinach|publisher=[[Dayton Daily News]]|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nkKAHM |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>

By September 18, the number of people sickened by the ''E. coli'' laced fresh spinach reached 111.<ref>{{cite news|title=E. coli spinach scare increases to 21 states|date=September 19, 2006|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/HEALTH/09/18/tainted.spinach/index.html|publisher=CNN|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nkd3Wp |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>

On September 19, it was reported that there may be a link to a further death in [[Ohio]] and [[irrigation]] water is being investigated as a possible source.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/mld/mercurynews/rss/15554157.htm?source=syn|title=Farm water is suspected in outbreak|date=September 19, 2006|publisher=[[Mercury News]]|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nlzgwS |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>

This is the 9th outbreak traced to the [[Salinas Valley]] in California and the 25th leafy green ''E. coli'' outbreak ([[spinach]] or lettuce) in the United States since 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foodsafetynetwork.ca/en/article-details.php?a=3&c=14&sc=98&id=903|title=Outbreaks of foodborne illness linked to fresh lettuce and spinach since 1993|date=September 18, 2006|work=Food Safety Network|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20060927211302/http%3A//www.foodsafetynetwork.ca/en/article-details.php%3Fa%3D3%26c%3D14%26sc%3D98%26id%3D903 |archivedate = September 27, 2006|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

On September 20, the CDC announced that the genetic fingerprint, a [[PFGE]] pattern, of [[E. coli O157|''E. coli'' O157]] isolated from an opened package of "[[Dole Food Company|Dole]] Baby Spinach, Best if Used by August 30" packed by [[Natural Selection (food company)|Natural Selection]] in the refrigerator of an ill New Mexico resident matched that of the outbreak strain.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cdc.gov/foodborne/ecolispinach/092006.htm|title=Update on Multi-State Outbreak of E. coli O157:H7 Infections From Fresh Spinach,September 20, 2006|date=September 20, 2006|work=[[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]]|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nmea0C |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>
On September 25, consumer advocates and lawmakers began urging tougher rules for fields and processing plants.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/health/2006-09-24-produce-rules_x.htm | work=USA Today | title=Safety advocates, growers debate produce rules | first=John | last=Ritter | date=October 5, 2006 | accessdate=April 22, 2010|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nmmBsZ |archivedate = December 19, 2010}}</ref>

On September 27, a Pittsford woman filed a lawsuit concerning this matter, stating that the tainted spinach has made her ill. See [http://www.democratandchronicle.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20060927/NEWS01/609270327/1002 Pittsford Woman Files Tainted Spinach Lawsuit]. This source also stated that additional lawsuits were being filed nationwide.

On September 29, the FDA downgraded the warning, now only warning against specific brands packaged on specific dates, instead of just fresh spinach in general.<ref name="ReutersFDAreducewarning">[http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/T/TAINTED_SPINACH?SITE=7219&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2006-09-29-20-28-40 (Reuters)] {{dead link|date=September 2010}}</ref>

==== October ====
On October 5, 2006, the FBI has launched a criminal investigation into this matter.<ref>[http://www.ecommercetimes.com/perl/search.pl?query=FDA Criminal Probe launched into the Spinach E. coli incident] {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nn0Fsf|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref><ref>[http://www.technewsworld.com/perl/story/53460.html FBI investigates Spinach E. coli incident as a criminal matter]  {{Wayback|url=http://www.technewsworld.com/perl/story/53460.html|date =20071209164040}}</ref><ref>[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/200609/18/health/main2016329.shtml CBS News: Feds investigate outbreak] {{WebCite|url=http://www.webcitation.org/5v6nnqRAd|date =December 19, 2010| accessdate= 20 December 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>

On October 9, 2006, a popular brand of lettuce grown in California's Salinas Valley, the region at the center of the nationwide spinach scare has been recalled over concerns about ''E. coli'' contamination.

On October 26, 2006, some of the largest grocery chains, including [[Vons]], [[New Albertsons Inc.|Albertsons]], [[Ralphs]] and others, sent a letter to the farmer's associations, giving them 6 weeks to come up with a plan to prevent problems like the E. coli breakout from happening again.

==== Overall toll ====
The overall toll of the spinach incident was 199 people in 28 states being infected, resulting in 141 hospitalizations, 31 people having kidney failure, and three deaths.<ref>Surak, John G. "A Recipe for Safe Food: ISO 22000 and HACCP". ''Quality Progress''. October 2007. p. 21.</ref>

